  "summary": "The narrator questions Geraldine about a laundry delivery made to No. 19. Geraldine consults her notebook, noting that at 1:35, a large basket of laundry was delivered while Miss Pemmican was out. She describes the driver as an ordinary, older man who drove the wrong way down the street, carried the basket to the back door, and wiped sweat from his face before driving off. Before leaving, the narrator advises Geraldine to keep a mysterious fruit knife that does not seem to belong to anyone.\n\nLater, Mrs. Rivale enters the \"Pavilion of the Peacock\" bar in a distressed state. She complains to the bartender, Fried, about being subjected to deception and evasion, stating she can no longer tolerate being treated poorly by people who do not tell her the whole truth. Fried consoles her and eventually advises her to go home to avoid the approaching rain.\n\nUpon arriving at her house, which smells of cabbage, fish, and eucalyptus, Mrs. Rivale is informed by a voice from the corner that a gentleman is waiting for her upstairs. She enters and finds Detective Chief Inspector Hakast sitting in her home. Hakast explains he traveled to London for work and wishes to discuss \"small matters\" regarding Harry. Although Mrs. Rivale defensively claims her business with Harry is over and that she has already provided all the information she can, she eventually agrees to listen to the detail Hakast wishes to discuss.",
